ProcedureHelp.#cdata:
Syntax: PROC PRINCOMP <options> ; 
    BY variables ; 
    FREQ variable ; 
    ID variables ; 
    PARTIAL variables ; 
    VAR variables ; 
    WEIGHT variable ; 

The PRINCOMP procedure performs principal component analysis. As input you can use raw data, 
a correlation matrix, a covariance matrix, or a sum-of-squares-and-crossproducts (SSCP) matrix. 
You can create output data sets containing eigenvalues, eigenvectors, and standardized or 
unstandardized principal component scores. 

Principal component analysis is a multivariate technique for examining relationships among 
several quantitative variables. The choice between using factor analysis and using principal 
component analysis depends in part on your research objectives. You should use the PRINCOMP 
procedure if you are interested in summarizing data and detecting linear relationships. You 
can use principal components to reduce the number of variables in regression, clustering, 
and so on.

StatementHelp.#cdata:
Syntax: PARTIAL variables ;

If you want to analyze a partial correlation or covariance matrix, specify the names of the numeric 
variablesto be partialed out in the PARTIAL statement.

Syntax: VAR variables ;

The VAR statement lists the numeric variables to be analyzed. If you omit the VAR statement, 
all numeric variables not specified in other statements are analyzed.
